Loan Data from Prosper Marketplace Exploration¶

by Maryam Shakeri¶

Investigation Overview¶

We investigate loan status and employment status and want to know how other factors like BorrowerAPR, ProsperRating (numeric), CreditScoreRangeLower, InquiriesLast6Months, and IncomeRange affect them. Relationships between different variables are examined.

Dataset Overview¶

Prosper Marketplace, Inc. was founded in 2005 as the first peer-to-peer lending marketplace in San Francisco, California. Prosper Funding LLC, one of its subsidiaries, operates Prosper.com, a website where individuals can either invest in personal loans or request to borrow money. Prosper has facilitated more than 17 billion dollars in loans to more than 1,030,000 people (accessed on 11/11/2020, source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prosper_Marketplace). Through Prosper, people can invest in each other in a way that is financially and socially rewarding. Borrowers apply online for a fixed-rate, fixed-term loan between 2,000 and 40,000. Individuals and institutions can invest in the loans and earn attractive returns. Prosper handles all loans servicing on behalf of the matched borrowers and investors. Prosper Marketplace is backed by leading investors including Sequoia Capital, Francisco Partners, Institutional Venture Partners, and Credit Suisse NEXT Fund (accessed on 11/11/2020, source: https://www.prosper.com/about)

A small subset of data has been picked from the origin prosper data to do some exploration on it. The cleaned subset (df_sub_clean) has 14 columns, and 83982 rows. The columns are ListingKey, ListingCreationDate, Term, LoanStatus, BorrowerAPR, ProsperRating (numeric), ListingCategory (numeric), EmploymentStatus, CreditScoreRangeLower, InquiriesLast6Months, IncomeRange, StatedMonthlyIncome, MonthlyLoanPayment and Year_listingCreation (created column includes the years of the 'ListingCreationDate') for each borrower.

The Employment Status and Their Loan Status¶

The vast majority of people applied for a loan from Prosper Marketplace was Employed (79.3%). About 9.4% and 5.3% were Full-time, and Self-employed, respectively. A minor portion of them is Not employed, Retired, and Part-time. For most Employed people, the loan status is Current and then Completed and Chargedoff, respectively. For Full-time people, the loan status is Completed and for Self-employed ones is Current.

The Average of BorrowerAPR versus The Year_listingCreation for Loan Status from 2009 through 2014¶

The highest APRs belong to the Chargedoff across the years. For the Current, the lowest APR was in 2010, and for the rest was in 2009. All loan status had the highest APRs in 2011. After 2011, the amount of APR had reduced for all. Before 2010, there is no Current status.

BorrowerAPR versus InquiriesLast6Months for Completed and Defaulted loans:¶

Defaulted loans have fewer inquiries with higher APRs compared to Completed loans. Completed loans are more spread out in inquiries. It seems that fewer inquiries do not have a strong influence on reducing the amount of APR.

BorrowerAPR versus CreditScoreRangeLower for Completed and Defaulted loans:¶

APR and CreditScoreRangeLower are scattered for both Completed and Defaulted loans. Most Defaulted loans have higher APR and less CreditScoreRangeLower compared to Completed. As seen, both Completed and Defaulted loans with less CreditScoreRangeLower have higher APRs. By increasing CreditScoreRangeLower, their APRs are reducing. The BorrowerAPR has a moderate negative correlation with the 'CreditScoreRangeLower'.

ProsperRating (numeric) versus LoanStatus in different Term of loans:¶

For 12-month-term loans, the Current and Defaulted loans have higher prosper-ratings. Also, the Current loan is more spread out in the prosper-rating compared to the others. The Completed loan has a prosper-rating between 2 and 3.

For 36-month-term loans, the Current and Chargedoff loans have higher prosper-ratings. All have wider distributions compared to the other Terms (12 and 60).

For 60-month-term loans, as seen, the distribution of prosper-rating is the same for the Completed, Chargedoff, and Defaulted loans.

ProsperRating (numeric) versus EmploymentStatus in different Term of loans:¶

For 12-month-term loans, Full-time people have higher prosper-rating. The Self-employed people have a prosper-rating between 2 and 3.

For 36-month-term loans, the Other has less prosper-rating, and the Employed, Self-employed and Not employed people have higher values (the distribution of prosper-rating for the Employed and Self-employed is right-skewed and for Not employed is left-skewed).

For 60-month-term loans, the highest prosper-rating belongs to the Retired people.

The IncomeRange for Different Loan Status across The Loan Terms¶

Most loans with Term 12 are Completed that have income range of 50,000-74,999 dollars. Then, the income ranges were 100,000+, and 25,000-49,999 and 75,000-99,999 dollars, respectively. Most loans with Term 36 and 60 are Current with income range of 50,000-74,999, and 25,000-49,999 dollars. In 36-month loans, after the Current, the most is Completed loan with an income range of 25,000-49,999 and 50,000-74,999 dollars.

# For Term = 12, use group_by() and size() to get the number of LoanStatus and each combination of the two variable levels as a pandas Series and then use .reset_index() to convert a series into a dataframe object
df_1=df_status.query('Term==12').groupby(['IncomeRange', 'LoanStatus'])['ListingKey'].size().reset_index()
# Use DataFrame.pivot() to rearrange the data, to have IncomeRange, on rows
df_1 = df_1.pivot('IncomeRange', 'LoanStatus', 'ListingKey')

The IncomeRange for Different Employment Status across The Loan Terms¶

In all 12, 36, and 60 Terms, most Employed people have an income range of 50,000-74,999 and 25,000-49,999 dollars who applied for loans. Also, in Term 12, most of them that applied for a loan had an income range of 100,000+ dollars.
